hands_on_practices.solution:
State 3 is absorbing; the transient states are $1$ and $2$. Let $Q$ be the $2\times 2$ submatrix of transitions among transient states:
$$
Q=\begin{pmatrix}
0.80 & 0.15\\
0.30 & 0.50
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
The fundamental matrix is $N=(I-Q)^{-1}$. Compute
$$
I-Q=\begin{pmatrix}
1-0.80 & -0.15\\
-0.30 & 1-0.50
\end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix}
0.20 & -0.15\\
-0.30 & 0.50
\end{pmatrix},
$$
with determinant
$$
\det(I-Q)=0.20\cdot 0.50-(-0.15)\cdot(-0.30)=0.10-0.045=0.055.
$$
Thus
$$
N=(I-Q)^{-1}=\frac{1}{0.055}\begin{pmatrix}
0.50 & 0.15\\
0.30 & 0.20
\end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix}
\frac{100}{11} & \frac{30}{11}\\
\frac{60}{11} & \frac{40}{11}
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
Let $m=N\mathbf{1}$ be the vector of expected steps to absorption, where $\mathbf{1}=(1,1)^{\mathsf{T}}$. Then
$$
m=\begin{pmatrix}
\frac{100}{11} & \frac{30}{11}\\
\frac{60}{11} & \frac{40}{11}
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
1\\
1
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
\frac{130}{11}\\
\frac{100}{11}
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
For absorbing chains, the variance vector $v$ of the absorption time satisfies
$$
v=(2N-I)m-m^{\circ 2},
$$
where $m^{\circ 2}$ denotes the elementwise square of $m$ and $I$ is the $2\times 2$ identity. Compute
$$
2N-I=\begin{pmatrix}
\frac{200}{11} & \frac{60}{11}\\
\frac{120}{11} & \frac{80}{11}
\end{pmatrix}
-
\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 0\\
0 & 1
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
\frac{189}{11} & \frac{60}{11}\\
\frac{120}{11} & \frac{69}{11}
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
Then
$$
(2N-I)m=
\begin{pmatrix}
\frac{189}{11} & \frac{60}{11}\\
\frac{120}{11} & \frac{69}{11}
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
\frac{130}{11}\\
\frac{100}{11}
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
\frac{30570}{121}\\
\frac{22500}{121}
\end{pmatrix},
\quad
m^{\circ 2}=
\begin{pmatrix}
\left(\frac{130}{11}\right)^{2}\\
\left(\frac{100}{11}\right)^{2}
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
\frac{16900}{121}\\
\frac{10000}{121}
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
Hence
$$
v=
\begin{pmatrix}
\frac{30570}{121}-\frac{16900}{121}\\
\frac{22500}{121}-\frac{10000}{121}
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
\frac{13670}{121}\\
\frac{12500}{121}
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
Starting from State $1$, the variance is $v_{1}=\frac{13670}{121}\approx 112.975\ldots$, which rounds to three significant figures as $113$.
